Jon, 

To clarify a point that you made in your message to the BIND mailing list:

CSNET is about to turn on a "blockaddr" module which will warn+accept and then
(later) warn+return mail addressed to old non-domain-style addresses.  (The
warning will indicate what the new domain-style address is).  So blockaddr will
apply to messages addressed as: "foo@oldhost" or "foo@oldhost.csnet" or
"foo%oldhost@relay.cs.net" or "foo%oldhost.csnet@relay.cs.net".  Blockaddr will
NOT apply to the "foo%newdomain@relay.cs.net" addresses that we get from non-MX
hosts.

On a related point, we're curious about what percentage of sites are able to
send directly to MX'd hosts these days.  Guesses anyone?  We'd like to send our
mail out as "From: user@domain" instead of "From: user%domain@relay.cs.net" but
we can't do that until the vast majority of people support MX.  Alternatively,
if there were some way of getting an informal list of those who support MX's we
could send out "From: user@domain" to them, at least.  An idea we tried once
before to create such a list worked pretty well so I'd like to try it again:

If you know of hosts or subdomains that support MX, please send a note to
"can-do-mx@relay.cs.net" where the text of the note is a list of the hosts or
subdomains.  Use any format you like, but preferably something like:
	*.cs.somewhere.edu
	*.math.somewhere.edu
	vax.ee.somewhere.edu
I'll summarize the results to the lists.

Thanks,
Dan

